1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 g6 3. e4 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Be2 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 Bd7 11. f3 Bc6 12. O-O a5 13. b3 Nd7 14. Rab1 Nc5 15. Rfd1 Qc7 16. Bf1 (16. Nd5 { Black is fine allowing Nd5 from White since he can just play Bxd5. In the Accelerated Dragon, it is the fianchetto bishop and Nc5 that are the strongest pieces in the endgames as you'll see below often. } 16... Bxd5 17. cxd5 Rfc8) 16... Rfc8 17. Kh1 Qb6 18. a3 Qc7 19. Nd5 Qd8 20. Bg5 Bxd5 21. exd5 a4 { Either White gets his pawn structure destroyed or allow Black's knight into b3, a relatively strong outpost. } 22. b4 Nb3 23. Qe3 Bf6 24. Re1 Bxg5 25. Qxg5 e5 26. Qe3 (26. Qxd8+ Rxd8 { This would lead to a favorable knight vs bishop endgame due to the permanent outpost on d4. }) 26... Qh4 27. Rbd1 Nd4 28. Bd3 b6 29. Kg1 Ra7 30. f4 Re7 31. fxe5 Rxe5 32. Qf2 Nf3+!! { Leads to series of forcing moves. } 33. gxf3 (33. Qxf3 Rxe1+) 33... Rg5+ 34. Kf1 Qh3+ 35. Ke2 Rg2 36. Rf1 Re8+ 37. Kd2 Qxf3! { No rush in taking the queen yet. It can't go anywhere, so calmly take more pawns. } 38. Qxg2 Qxg2+ 39. Kc3 Qa2 { And the next pawn (a3) falls too } 40. Rb1 (40. Ra1 Qb3+ 41. Kd2 Qb2+ 42. Bc2 Qd4+ 43. Bd3 Re3) 40... Re3 41. Rfd1 Qxh2 42. c5 dxc5 43. bxc5 bxc5 44. Kc4 Qd6 45. Rb5 Qf4+ 46. Kxc5 Qf3 47. Kd4 Re8 48. Rbb1 Qf6+ 49. Kc4 Rc8+ 50. Kb5 Qc3 51. Rb4 Qxa3 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


