1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. d3 d6 6. Nge2 (6. Nh3 { Also a playable move to prepare 0-0 and not blocking the f-pawn to keep f4 pushes open. } 6... h5!? { The drawback of Nh3 is White cannot play h4 to prevent the h-file from opening up. Black should take advantage of it. } 7. O-O h4 8. g4 Nf6 9. f3 d5 { White's light squared bishop is blocked from the action }) 6... e5 7. O-O Nge7 8. f4 O-O 9. h3 Nd4 10. g4 (10. Be3 Be6 11. g4 f5) (10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 Nxe2+ 12. Qxe2 exf4) 10... f5!? { Contesting the kingside with another pawn. Similar pawn structure, but the knight on d4 allows Black to play a bit more dynamically. } 11. exf5 gxf5 12. fxe5 dxe5 13. gxf5 Nexf5 14. Ne4 Kh8 { Preparing Rg8 next } *


