1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. f4 Bg7 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bb5 { The other popular move. I recommend Nd4 right away, which often transposes to the same setups and ideas as the Bc4 lines in the earlier chapter. } 5... Nd4 6. O-O (6. Bc4 e6 7. O-O Ne7 8. d3 O-O { [%cal Gd7d5] }) (6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Ne2 Nh6 8. O-O O-O 9. d3 d5) 6... Nxb5 { If White doesn't move the bishop, just take it! } 7. Nxb5 d5 8. exd5 a6 9. Nc3 Nf6 10. d4 { Otherwise you just recapture on d5 with a pleasant endgame using the bishop pair. } 10... Nxd5 11. dxc5 Nxc3 12. Qxd8+ Kxd8 13. bxc3 Bxc3 14. Rb1 Kc7 { The bishop pair is dominating for now. White could force an exchange with Bb2, but the superior pawn structure is still an advantage you can press in the endgame } 15. Bb2 Bxb2 16. Rxb2 Be6 *


