1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nde2 { A sideline to set up the kingside fianchetto and play more solid in the center with the connected knights } (6. Nb3 d6 7. Be2 Bxc3+!? { Again we see the thematic Bxc3+ to play against the double isolated c-pawns. White's position is fairly awkward here, which justifies giving up the fianchetto bishop a bit more. } 8. bxc3 Nf6 9. f3 O-O 10. O-O d5 { Black should have good play all around as long White doesn't get enough play against the dark squares on the kingside. }) 6... Nf6 7. g3 b5! { Overworking the Nc3. b4 is a real threat, gaining space on the queenside as well as attempt to win the important e4 pawn for White } 8. Bg2 (8. Nxb5 Nxe4 { At the cost of both center pawns, White has zero compensation }) 8... b4 9. Nd5 O-O 10. O-O a5 11. h3 Ba6 12. Be3 { Pretty active position for Black with both bishops on long diagonals. Black has no real weaknesses for White to exploit } *


