[UTCTime "11:26:31"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 { Here both sides enter the main line of the 5. Nc3 variation of the Accelerated Dragon. Common moves are Bc4, f3 (basically refuted, see next chapter), Be2, and Nxc6. There will be three chapters for Bc4 and one chapter each for the other two lines . This study we will start with Bc4, the most challenging one (arguably the only challenging one) } 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3 (8. f3? { Mistake! Refer to the chapter "Must-Know Mini-Trap!!" }) 8... d6 9. f3 Na5 10. h4 h5 11. Qd2 Bd7 12. O-O-O Rb8 { Rc8 is far more common to aim for Nc4 next. Rb8 is a sideline which leads to dynamic play down the b-file. The main idea is to play b5 and only then Nc4. Once White is provoked into playing Bxc4, you get pressure on the vulnerable b2 pawn. } 13. Bh6 Nxb3+ 14. Nxb3 (14. cxb3 { If cxb3, you can take a step back with the attack and just focus on playing solid. White has already damaged their own pawn structure. }) (14. axb3 b5 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Nd5 b4 { If Black can double up on the a-file, White's king will be in grave danger }) 14... a5 { Launching a pawn storm in order to break open White's queenside defense } 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Nd4 b5 17. g4 e6 { Stopping Nd5 and then continuing the rush of the queenside pawns. } *


