1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3 d6 9. h3 { The h3 lines are harmless } 9... Na5 10. O-O b6 { Because White has committed h3 early on, it is important to add as much pressure to the e4 pawn as possible to provoke f3 from White. Then the dark squares around their king is weakened. } 11. f4 (11. Re1 Bb7 12. Bg5 Nxb3 13. axb3 h6 14. Bh4 Qd7) 11... Nxb3 12. axb3 Bb7 13. Qd3 { The bishop exert a lot of pressure down the long diagonals } *


