1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Be2 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 a5 11. f3 a4 12. Rc1 Be6 13. Rc2 Nd7 14. O-O Qa5 15. Nd5 Rfe8 16. Rfc1 Kf8 17. Qxa5 Rxa5 { Black should be happy to go into a queenless endgame. He has a nice outpost for the knight on c5 and the long a1-h8 diagonal. } 18. Nc7 Rc8 19. Nxe6+ fxe6 20. Kf2 Nc5 21. h4 Ra6 22. Ke1 Kf7 23. Kd2 a3 24. bxa3 (24. b4 Nb3+! 25. axb3 a2 { Amazing illustration of the power of the long diagonal. White cannot prevent a1 Q, and has to give up a rook. }) 24... Rxa3 { Now there are two clear pawn weaknesses on a2 and c4 } 25. Rb1 Rc7 26. Rb5 Be5 27. g4 Bg3 28. h5 gxh5 29. gxh5 Be1+ 30. Kxe1 Rxe3 31. Kf2 Ra3 32. Rb1 e5 33. Bf1 Rc8 34. Be2 Rca8 35. Rbb2 h6 36. Bf1 Kf6 37. Rd2 Rc3 38. Rdc2 Rca3 39. Rd2 Kg5 40. Kg2 Kxh5 41. Be2 Kg5 42. Bd1 Kf4 43. Kf1 { Strong knight vs bad bishop endgame. And the black king has all these dark square holes to invade in } 43... Rd3 44. Rxd3 Nxd3 45. Rh2 Ke3 46. Rg2 Ra3 47. Bb3 Nc1 48. Rb2 Nxb3 49. axb3 Kxf3 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


