1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rb8 11. Bb3 Na5 12. Bh6 Bxh6 13. Qxh6 b5 14. Nd5 Nxb3+ 15. Nxb3 e5 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. h4 Rb6 18. h5 Qe7 19. hxg6 fxg6 { White's attack has slowed down, as long as the h7 pawn is defended. Black has the next move with pressure along the c-file. } 20. Qe3 Be6 21. Rhf1 Rc6 22. f4 Qc7 23. Rd2 a5 24. Kb1 a4 25. Nc1 b4 26. Rdf2 exf4 27. Rxf4 Rc8 { Interesting position due to seemingly separate battles of the major pieces being played: One along the f-file and one along the c-file. } 28. Rf6 Rxc2 29. Rxe6 Qc4 30. Ref6 a3 { The current threat is Rxb2+ Ka1 Rb1+! Kxb1 Qc2+ Ka1 Qc2# } 31. bxa3 bxa3 32. Qxa3 Rxc1+ 33. Rxc1 Qxe4+ 34. Kb2 Qe5+ 35. Rc3 Rb8+ 36. Kc2 Qxf6 { Simplifying into a queen and rook endgame up a pawn. The far safer king makes the win very straightforward. } 37. Rf3 Qd4 38. Rb3 Qe4+ 39. Kc1 Qe1+ 40. Kc2 Qe2+ 41. Kb1 Qd1+ 42. Qc1 Rxb3+ 43. axb3 Qxb3+ 44. Ka1 Qa4+ 45. Kb2 Qb5+ 46. Ka1 Qc5 47. Qd2 h5 { Black just has to slowly advance the kingside pawns and look for a queen trade, while avoiding any perpetual checks. } 48. Kb1 Kg7 49. Qb2+ Qe5 50. Qb7+ Kh6 51. Kc1 d5 52. Kd1 Qe4 53. Qb2 Kg5 54. Qd2+ Kg4 55. Qh6 g5 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


