1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. e4 Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Be2 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Bg5 O-O 10. Qd2 a5 11. Rc1 a4 12. f3 Be6 13. Nb5 Bd7 14. Nd4 Be8 { An awkward looking move, but reasonable to allow the standard Nd7 retreat. } 15. O-O Nd7 16. Rfd1 Nc5 17. Be3 Qa5 18. Qc2 Bd7 19. Bf1 Rfc8 20. Qb1 Ne6 21. Ne2 Nc5 22. Nd4 Bf6 23. Kh1 h5 24. Rc2 Na6 25. a3 { Innocent looking pawn move to prevent Nb4, but now there's an outpost on b3! } 25... Nc5 { Knight comes right back! } 26. Ne2 { Knight comes right back! } 26... Nb3 27. Nf4 Bc6 28. Nd5 Bxd5 29. Rxd5 Qc7 30. Qd1 Ra5 31. g3 Rxd5 32. exd5 Qd7 33. Qd3 Nc5 34. Bxc5 Rxc5 35. b4 axb3 36. Qxb3 { We reach a typical Accelerated Dragon endgame pawn structure. Black has a completely safe king while White's pawns are overextended. Now Black has to pile up against the weak pawns } 36... Qc7 37. Kg2 Qa5 38. Qxb7 Qxa3 39. Qb1 Ra5 40. Qd1 Qc5 41. Qe2 Qa7 42. f4 Ra3 43. f5 { An interesting attempt to break Black's solid kingside, but it also opens up White's kingside as well, which evidently backfires } 43... Re3 44. Qf2 Qd4 45. fxg6 Qe4+ 46. Kh3 Rf3 47. gxf7+ Kxf7 48. Qe2 Qf5+ 49. Kg2 Rxf1 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


