1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rb8 11. h4 b5!? { An ambitious gambit. Surprisingly, White has 3 options to capture the b5 pawn with, but they all lead to trouble. } 12. Bb3 (12. Bxb5 Nxd4) (12. Ndxb5 Ne5 13. Be2 Qa5 { This doesn't lose a piece, but Black gets a quick attack with the now semi-open b- and a- files. }) (12. Ncxb5 Na5 13. Na3 (13. Be2 e5) 13... Nxc4 14. Nxc4 Qc8 { Also leading to great pressure on the queenside files. }) 12... Na5 13. h5 Nc4 14. Bxc4 bxc4 15. hxg6 fxg6 16. Bh6 Qb6 17. b3 { These innocent pawn moves by white on the queenside are opportunities for Black to invade in the future. } 17... cxb3 18. axb3 Bxh6 19. Qxh6 Rf7 { Kingside is pretty safe, so onwards to the queenside! } 20. Qg5 Rc8 21. Kb2 a5 22. Rd3 a4 { Classic pawn break to open up a file } 23. Nf5 Bxf5 24. exf5 axb3 25. fxg6 bxc2+ 26. Kxc2 hxg6 27. Rh6 (27. Qxg6+ Rg7 { Counterthreat! And now it is Black with the initiative. }) 27... Qf2+ 28. Rd2 Qa7 29. Rxg6+ Kf8 30. Qb5 Rh7 31. Kd3 Rc5 32. Qb3 Qa6+ 33. Ke3 Rh1 34. Ne4 Re5 { Black has to be cautious that White doesn't have any points of entry with the major pieces. } 35. Kf4 (35. Qb8+ Kf7) 35... Rxe4+ 36. fxe4 Qf1+ 37. Qf3 Qc1 38. Qd3 Qa1 39. Rg3 Nh5+ { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


